Well. he signed today. The consensus on this one stayed low until the end. A bit of post-mortem why (in my view):
- early on, the prevailing opinion was that after the health care debacle in the spring, no new attempts will be made this year;
- later, when the issue appeared in the tax bill, the view shifted that it won't survive in the final version owing to resistance by some Senate Rs;
- finally, when the Senate voted for it, there was skepticism that the law can be signed before end-2017 (including until yesterday, because of PAYGO provisions). All these proved wrong. What did the GJO forecasters do wrong (in my view):
 - a bit of the standard stuff of hedgehog thinking and confirmation bias - once a view is formed, people are reluctant to change it quickly and are giving more credence to information that supports their view;
 - assuming that if a few R Senators voted against the health care bill repeal in the spring, they will do so in the fall as well. In fact, it seems that the pressure these Senators experienced after their earlier vote led to them settling for not-too-credible promises in exchange for their supporting vote this time; 
 - paying too much attention to technical details around signing and underestimating Republicans' political will to get something done before end-2017
